Neural Networks

Neural Network with Boston Dataset

Here we are going to use the Boston datset in order to train a neural network to determine the median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000s. A brief summary of the headers is listed below:

Concerns housing values in suburbs of Boston.

1. CRIM: per capita crime rate by town
2. ZN: proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
3. INDUS: proportion of non-retail business acres per town
4. CHAS: Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)
5. NOX: nitric oxides concentration (parts per 10 million)
6. RM: average number of rooms per dwelling
7. AGE: proportion of owner-occupied units built prior to 1940
8. DIS: weighted distances to five Boston employment centres
9. RAD: index of accessibility to radial highways
10. TAX: full-value property-tax rate per $10,000
11. PTRATIO: pupil-teacher ratio by town
12. B: 1000(Bk - 0.63)^2 where Bk is the proportion of blacks by town
13. LSTAT: % lower status of the population
14. MEDV: Median value of owner-occupied homes in $1000's

Split data 

library(caTools)
split = sample.split(scaled$medv, SplitRatio = 0.7)

train = subset(scaled, split == T)
test = subset(scaled, split == F)

Being Lazy, Easy Function Creation 

n = names(train)
f = as.formula(paste("medv ~", 
                     paste(n[!n %in% "medv"], 
                           collapse = " + ")))
f
## medv ~ crim + zn + indus + chas + nox + rm + age + dis + rad + 
##     tax + ptratio + black + lstat

Creating the Neural Network

Hidden refers to the perceptrons at each stage of the neural network. Note the \(5\) and \(3\) and the plot below. We select linear.output = TRUE because the solution is continuous (not a classification).

library(neuralnet)
nn = neuralnet(f, data = train, 
               hidden = c(5, 3), 
               linear.output = TRUE)

Plot of the Neural Network

This is likely to be an incredibly unlikely source of information. One of the issues with deep learning is that it is indeed deep. The more perceptrons used, the less interpretable the model becomes.

plot(nn)

Predicted Values 

predicted.nn.values = compute(nn, test[1:13])

# Inverting the scaling done before.
true.predictions = predicted.nn.values$net.result * 
                    (max(data$medv) - min(data$medv)) + min(data$medv)

# Rescale the test data
test.r = (test$medv)*(max(data$medv) - min(data$medv)) + min(data$medv)

# Check MSE
MSE.nn = sum((test.r - true.predictions)^2)/nrow(test)

# Create data.frame to view accuracy solution. 
error.df = data.frame(test.r, true.predictions)

Neural Network with the Banknote Authentication Data Set

Data Set Information:

Data were extracted from images that were taken from genuine and forged banknote-like specimens. For digitization, an industrial camera usually used for print inspection was used. The final images have 400x 400 pixels. Due to the object lens and distance to the investigated object gray-scale pictures with a resolution of about 660 dpi were gained. Wavelet Transform tool were used to extract features from images.

1. variance of Wavelet Transformed image (continuous)
2. skewness of Wavelet Transformed image (continuous)
3. curtosis of Wavelet Transformed image (continuous)
4. entropy of image (continuous)
5. class (integer)

Click here for information on wavelet transformation.

library(data.table)
data = fread("https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/machine-learning-databases/00267/data_banknote_authentication.txt")

               hidden = c(5, 3), 
               linear.output = FALSE)

Plot of the Neural Network 

plot(nn)

Predicted Values 

predicted.nn.values = compute(nn, test[1:4])

# Inverting the scaling done before.
true.predictions = predicted.nn.values$net.result * 
                    (max(data$V5) - min(data$V5)) + min(data$V5)

# Rescale the test data
test.r = (test$V5)*(max(data$V5) - min(data$V5)) + min(data$V5)

# Check MSE
MSE.nn = sum((test.r - true.predictions)^2)/nrow(test)

# Create data.frame to view accuracy solution. 
error.df = data.frame(test.r, true.predictions)

Bank Authentication Data Set with Random Forest 

library(randomForest)
data$V5 = as.factor(data$V5)
split = sample.split(data$V5, SplitRatio = 0.70)

train = subset(data, split == TRUE)
test = subset(data, split == FALSE)

Solutions are probabilities of belonging to the 0 or 1 class.

Random Forest Model

Good model!
